Chapter 3.3

  • Aesthetic is a visual property of the objects in your plot
    • size, the shape, or the color of points
    • ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = class))
    • ggplot(data = mpg) +
      • All class diffent color geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = class))
    • ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, alpha = class))
    • ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, shape = class))
    • ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy), color = blue)
      • All class same color

Continuous: displ, year, cty, hwy, cyl

The aesthetics change in size, shape, and color from categorical to continuous variables.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, shape = class, color = class, size = class))

Every variables has a diffent size, shape, and coloe from the other variables.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, stroke = 5))

Stroke aesthetic changes the border of the level.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, colour = displ < 5))

If you map an aesthetic to something other than a variable name, like aes(colour = displ < 5) the color of the levels stays blue untill it reaches the 5 mark in the x-axis then the color turnes red.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow = 2)

The advantages of using faceting instead of the colour aesthetic is that we can see the variables individually clearly on a separately plot. The disadvantages are that it makes it harder to compare the variables

  1. nrow shows you the numbers of row you have. ncol shows you the numbers of columns you have.Other options control the layout of the individual panels are scales, shrink, and labeller. facet_grid() dont have nrow and ncol arguments becaues the are unique values of variable that are specified by the rows and columns.

  2. When using facet_grid() you should usually put the variable with more unique levels in the columns becaues if it is layed our horizontally you can see the the value in the columns better.

Chapter 3.6

  • A geom is the geometrical object that a plot uses to represent data.
  • To change the geom in your plot, change the geom function that you add to ggplot()
    • ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))
    • ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))
  • geom_smooth() will draw a different line, with a different linetype, for each unique value of the variable that you map to linetype.
    • ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, linetype = drv))
    • geom_smooth() separates the cars into three lines based on their drv value
  • learn more about any single geom, use help: ?geom_smooth.
  • the group aesthetic by itself does not add a legend or distinguishing features to the geoms.
    • ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))
    • ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, group = drv))
    • ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv), show.legend = FALSE
  • To display multiple geoms in the same plot, add multiple geom functions to ggplot(): -ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) -This makes it possible to display different aesthetics in different layers.
    • ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + geom_point(mapping = aes(color = class)) + geom_smooth()

Chapter 3.7

  • Learn which stat a geom uses by doing ?geom_bar
    • Shows that the default value for stat is count, which means that geom_bar() uses stat_count(). stat_count()
    • ggplot(data = diamonds) + stat_count(mapping = aes(x = cut)) -Each column havd diffrent lables
  • Override defalt
    • Change the stat of geom_bar() from count (the default) to identity
  • where the height of the bar is generated by counting rows
    • ggplot(data = demo) + geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, y = freq), stat = identity)
  • stat_summary(), which summarises the y values for each unique x value, to draw attention to the summary that youre computing
    • ggplot(data = diamonds) + stat_summary( mapping = aes(x = cut, y = depth), fun.ymin = min, fun.ymax = max, fun.y = median)

3.7.1 Exercises

  1. The default geom associated with stat_summary() uses mean ans sd to gwt the middle point and end point of a line.
ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_pointrange(
    mapping = aes(x = cut, y = depth),
    stat = "summary",
    fun.ymin = min,
    fun.ymax = max,
    fun.y = median
  )

  1. geom_col() and geom_bar() are types of bar charts. geom_bar() makes the height of the bar proportional to the number of cases in each group.

  2. width, binwidth: Change the resolution of the data.
    geom, stat: Override the default connection between geom_bar() and stat_count().

  3. stat_smooth() compute the variables:
    y: predicted value
    ymin: lower value of the confidence interval
    ymax: upper value of the confidence interval
    se: standard error

Parameters thar control its behaviour: - formula - na.rm -methods
